In JavaScript, you can make HTTP requests using the built-in `fetch()` function or the `XMLHttpRequest` object. Here's how you can use both:

1. Using `fetch()`:

The `fetch()` function is a modern way to make HTTP requests in JavaScript. It returns a Promise that resolves to the Response object representing the response to the request. This response can then be parsed as JSON, text, or other formats.

Here's an example of making a GET request using `fetch()`:

```javascript
fetch('https://api.example.com/data')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // process the data here
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // handle any errors here
    console.error(error);
  });
```

You can also make POST, PUT, DELETE, and other types of HTTP requests by passing in an options object with the `method` property set to the desired method. For example, here's how you can make a POST request:

```javascript
const data = {
  name: 'John Doe',
  age: 30
};

fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json'
  },
  body: JSON.stringify(data)
})
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // process the data here
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // handle any errors here
    console.error(error);
  });
```

2. Using `XMLHttpRequest`:

The `XMLHttpRequest` object is an older way to make HTTP requests in JavaScript, but it's still widely used. It allows you to make requests asynchronously without blocking the rest of the page from loading.

Here's an example of making a GET request using `XMLHttpRequest`:

```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('GET', 'https://api.example.com/data');
xhr.responseType = 'json';
xhr.onload = function() {
  if (xhr.status === 200) {
    // process the data here
    console.log(xhr.response);
  } else {
    // handle any errors here
    console.error(xhr.statusText);
  }
};
xhr.send();
```

And here's an example of making a POST request using `XMLHttpRequest`:

```javascript
const data = {
  name: 'John Doe',
  age: 30
};

const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('POST', 'https://api.example.com/data');
xhr.setRequestHeader('Content-Type', 'application/json');
xhr.onload = function() {
  if (xhr.status === 200) {
    // process the data here
    console.log(xhr.response);
  } else {
    // handle any errors here
    console.error(xhr.statusText);
  }
};
xhr.send(JSON.stringify(data));
```

