To run two Docker apps on the same Ubuntu server with different domains, you can follow these steps:

1. Install and configure Nginx as a reverse proxy on your Ubuntu server, listening on ports 80 and 443 for HTTP and HTTPS traffic, respectively. You can follow this guide for installation and initial configuration: <https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-install-nginx-on-ubuntu-18-04-quickstart>
2. Create two separate Docker Compose files, one for each app, following the structure of your existing `docker-compose.yml` file. Make sure to give each service a unique name to avoid conflicts. For example, you can use `frontend-nsd` and `backend-nsd` for the nsd.newtablab.com app, and `frontend-www` and `backend-www` for the www.newstablab.com app.
3. Modify each `nginx` service in the Docker Compose files to listen on a unique port. For example, you can use port 8080 for nsd.newtablab.com and port 8081 for www.newstablab.com.
4. Create two Nginx configuration files, one for each app, that use the appropriate `server_name` directive and `proxy_pass` the requests to the appropriate Docker app and port.

Here's an example of how the Nginx configuration files could look like:

**nsd.newtablab.com**
```bash
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name nsd.newtablab.com;

  location / {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
  }
}
```
**www.newstablab.com**
```bash
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name www.newstablab.com;

  location / {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:8081;
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
  }
}
```
5. Add these Nginx configuration files to the appropriate Docker Compose file. You can mount a volume that contains the Nginx configuration files to the `/etc/nginx/conf.d` directory of the Nginx service, like this:

```yaml
nginx:
  volumes:
  - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d
```

6. Rename the Nginx configuration files to match the domain name, for example `nsd.newtablab.com.conf` and `www.newstablab.com.conf`.
7. Run the two Docker Compose files using `docker-compose up -d` and check that they are accessible using their respective domain names.

Note: Make sure your server has a valid SSL certificate for both domains if you want to enable HTTPS traffic.

