Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) and Parse Tree are both related to the parsing of programming languages, but they serve different purposes and have different structures.

A Parse Tree is a tree that represents the syntactic structure of a string according to a given grammar. It is typically generated by a parser and includes all the details of the grammar rules used to parse the input. A Parse Tree can be quite large and complex, and it includes many nodes that may not be relevant to the semantics of the program.

An Abstract Syntax Tree (AST), on the other hand, is a simplified version of a Parse Tree that focuses on the important semantic aspects of the program. It omits many of the details of the grammar rules and includes only the nodes that are necessary to represent the program's structure and semantics. An AST is typically generated from a Parse Tree by applying a series of simplification rules.

To implement both an Abstract Syntax Tree and a Parse Tree in Java using ANTLR, you can follow these general steps:

1. Define a grammar for the programming language you want to parse using ANTLR. The grammar will define the syntax of the language and provide the rules for constructing a Parse Tree.
2. Generate the parser and lexer classes from the ANTLR grammar using the ANTLR tool. These classes will provide the methods you need to parse input sentences and construct a Parse Tree.
3. Write a visitor or listener class that traverses the Parse Tree and constructs an Abstract Syntax Tree. The visitor or listener class should implement the appropriate interfaces provided by ANTLR and override the methods that correspond to the nodes in the Parse Tree.
4. In the overridden methods, you can create nodes in the AST that correspond to the relevant syntactic constructs in the programming language. You can use the factory pattern to create AST nodes and encapsulate the logic for creating different types of nodes.
5. Finally, you can use the AST to perform semantic analysis, code generation, or other tasks that require a program representation that focuses on the program's meaning rather than its syntax.

Here's a simple example of how to implement an Abstract Syntax Tree for arithmetic expressions using ANTLR and Java:

1. Define a grammar for arithmetic expressions in ANTLR:
```go
grammar Arithmetic;

prog:   stat+ ;

stat:   expr NEWLINE                # printExpr
    |   ID '=' expr NEWLINE         # assign
    |   NEWLINE                     # blank
    ;

expr:   expr op=('*' | '/') expr    # MulDiv
    |   expr op=('+' | '-') expr    # AddSub
    |   INT                         # int
    |   ID                          # id
    |   '(' expr ')'                # parens
    ;

MUL :   '*' ; // assigns token name to '*' operator
DIV :   '/' ; // assigns token name to '/' operator
ADD :   '+' ; // assigns token name to '+' operator
SUB :   '-' ; // assigns token name to '-' operator
ID  :   [a-z]+ ;      // match identifiers
INT :   [0-9]+ ;      // match integers
NEWLINE:'\r'? '\n' ;  // return newlines to parser (is end-statement signal)
WS  :   [ \t]+ -> skip ; // toss out whitespace
```
2. Generate the parser and lexer classes from the ANTLR grammar using the ANTLR tool.
3. Write a visitor class that traverses the Parse Tree and constructs an Abstract Syntax Tree:
```java
public class ASTBuilder extends ArithmeticBaseVisitor<ASTNode> {

    @Override
    public ASTNode visitProg(ArithmeticParser.ProgContext ctx) {
        return visitChildren(ctx);
    }

    @Override
    public ASTNode visitStat(ArithmeticParser.StatContext ctx) {
        if (ctx.printExpr() != null) {
            return visit(ctx.printExpr().expr());
        } else if (ctx.assign() != null) {
            ASTNode idNode = visit(ctx.assign().ID());
            ASTNode exprNode = visit(ctx.assign().expr());
            idNode.addChild(exprNode);
            return idNode;
        } else {
            return null;
        }
    }

    @Override
    public ASTNode visitExpr(ArithmeticParser.ExprContext ctx) {
        if (ctx. MulDiv() != null) {
            ASTNode leftNode = visit(ctx.expr(0));
            ASTNode rightNode = visit(ctx.expr(1));
            String op = ctx.MulDiv().getText();
            return new BinaryOperatorNode(op, leftNode, rightNode);
        } else if (ctx. AddSub() != null) {
            ASTNode leftNode = visit(ctx.expr(0));
            ASTNode rightNode = visit(ctx.expr(1));
            String op = ctx.AddSub().getText();
            return new BinaryOperatorNode(op, leftNode, rightNode);
        } else if (ctx.INT() != null) {
